{"type":"result","subtype":"success","is_error":false,"duration_ms":83644,"duration_api_ms":83589,"num_turns":8,"result":"","stop_reason":"end_turn","session_id":"acb6c234-cf24-4d97-b85f-b11daeeb27b9","total_cost_usd":0.3936986,"usage":{"input_tokens":7,"cache_creation_input_tokens":36475,"cache_read_input_tokens":170243,"output_tokens":2677,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":36475,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"},"modelUsage":{"claude-opus-4-6":{"inputTokens":7,"outputTokens":2677,"cacheReadInputTokens":170243,"cacheCreationInputTokens":36475,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":0.38005025,"contextWindow":200000,"maxOutputTokens":64000},"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001":{"inputTokens":14,"outputTokens":761,"cacheReadInputTokens":41556,"cacheCreationInputTokens":4539,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":0.01364835,"contextWindow":200000,"maxOutputTokens":32000}},"permission_denials":[],"structured_output":{"rulings":[{"amendment_id":"fr-5-5b9be0ac","decision":"reject","rationale":"The code's design is intentional and well-documented (lines 1442-1448). The spawn-time path (lines 985-990) already catches the definitive missing-binary case via ErrorKind::NotFound. For shebang scripts (#!/usr/bin/env node), if the interpreter is missing, Linux's execve() fails with ENOENT at the kernel level, which spawn() catches as BinaryNotFound — so the most important missing-interpreter case is already handled. The remaining post-spawn 127 scenario (e.g., bash starts but an internal command fails) is genuinely application-defined behavior: retrying may help if a deployment is completing or PATH is being updated. Reclassifying post-spawn 127 as non-retryable would create false terminal failures for wrapper scripts that use exit 127 for their own error conditions. Burning a few retry attempts on a broken wrapper is a less harmful failure mode than prematurely abandoning retries on a transiently misconfigured environment. The planner and Reviewer 1's technical analysis of the spawn-time vs post-spawn distinction is correct, and the 2-to-1 consensus reflects the stronger technical argument."}],"summary":"Rejected the sole disputed amendment (fr-5-5b9be0ac). The classify_exit_failure() stub is an intentional, documented design decision that correctly distinguishes spawn-time failures (where the OS definitively reports a missing binary) from post-spawn exits (where exit codes are application-defined). The most critical missing-interpreter case — shebang scripts with absent interpreters — is already caught at spawn time via ErrorKind::NotFound. Reclassifying post-spawn exit 127 as non-retryable would create false terminal failures for wrappers that use 127 for their own error signaling, which is a worse failure mode than burning a few retry attempts."},"fast_mode_state":"off","uuid":"109ade41-e06b-4d63-8f98-09ac9ee8000b"}
